Also we create a column called 'total_km' when we calculate the total distance traveled between the difference of longitude ('end_lng' - 'start_lng') and latitude ('end_lat' - 'start_lat') in kilometers with haversine function. And later we drop the columns 'start_lat', 'start_lng', 'end_lat', 'end_lng' becasue now we don't need these.

In [14]:
# We define haversine function
def haversine (lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2):
    rad = math.pi/180
    diff_lat = lat2 - lat1
    diff_lon = lon2 - lon1
    R = 6372.795477598
    a = (math.sin(rad*diff_lat/2))**2 + math.cos(rad*lat1) * math.cos(rad*lat2) * (math.sin(rad*diff_lon/2))**2
    distancia = 2*R*math.asin(math.sqrt(a))
    return distancia

# Now we are going to create a new column called 'total_dist' where we calculate the distance traveled.
distance_km = []
mesure = ride_bike.shape[0]
for x in range(mesure):
    lat1 = ride_bike.iloc[x, 3]
    lon1  = ride_bike.iloc[x, 4]
    lat2 = ride_bike.iloc[x, 5]
    lon2 = ride_bike.iloc[x, 6]
    distance = haversine(lat1, lon1 , lat2, lon2)
    distance_km.append(distance)
ride_bike['distance_km'] = distance_km

# Drop the columns 'start_lat', 'start_lng', 'end_lat', 'end_lng', we don't need its.
ride_bike = ride_bike.drop(['start_lat', 'start_lng', 'end_lat', 'end_lng'], axis=1)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

I perfomred the following operations on the original dataset:

  • I dropped columns that we don't need which they also have at the same time null values, and we also dropped rows with null values.
  • I change the type of the data of 'started_at' and 'ended_at' columns to Datetime to be able to get the data out.
  • I added new columns for later visualizate the graphs and do proportions. This columns are the day of the week, the duration in minutes whuch is the difference beteen the 'started_at' and 'ended_at' columns, and the distance in kilometeres which has been calculted ith the Haversine function on 'start_lat', 'start_lng', 'end_lat' and 'end_lng' columns.

After clean, there are 154771 rides in the dataset with 7 features (rideable_type, started_at, ended_at, member_casual, day_of_the_week, duration_min, distance_km).

The variables rideable_type and member_casual are categorical with the following levels:

  • rideable_type: electric_bike, docked_bike
  • member_casual: member, casual
  • day_of_the_week: Monday, Twuesday, Wednesday, Thursday, Friday, Saturday, Sunday

The variables 'started_at' and 'ended_at' are in Datetime for a better use.

The rest of variables how 'duration_min' and 'distance_km' are numeric.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in figuring out what features are best for predicting the follow questions:

  • How long does the average trip take?
  • When are most trips taken in dataset in terms of day of the week (Monday, Twuesday, Wednesday, Thursday, Friday, Saturday or Sunday). All the data taken is from July of 2020, the we don't need investigate nothing about month and year.
  • The above depend on if a user is a member or costumer?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that the variable 'duration_min' will be the most important for the investigation and I also expect that for more time of use greater distance travelled.

Just as importantly will be the variable 'started_at' for predicting when most trips is taken in terms of day of the week.

In addition to this, I think what the service will be more used by subscribers, and electrical bike than dicked bike.
